Data Exploration Project

Glen Lewis

2/18/2021

In 2015 the College Score Card started to be published. This score card include a once hard to find metric, reported earning by graduates. The following examines if schools who graduates earn more received more interest following 2015 when the first College Score Card with reported earnings was released.

Defining High and Low Earning Institutions

Initial visualization and descriptive statistics of the standardized earnings show mean standardized earnings is .403 standard deviations (sd) above 0, with the interquartile range being -.159 to .786. The density plot of standardized earnings show a distribution that is skewed right which is reinforced by the number and magnitudes of outliers seen in the boxplot. For the purposes of this analysis high earning institutions will be defined as those reporting earnings above the 75th percentile (.786) and conversely those institute reporting below the 25th percentile (-.159) will be defined as low earning institutes.

Did Potential Earning Opportunities Influence Index Score Prior to 2015

The following visualizations show the monthly standardized index for high and low earning institutes against reported earnings prior to the first score card release in 2015.

The first plot - for high earning institutes - shows the monthly average trend index score from 2013 - 2014 plotted against their reported graduate income. The plot appears to show that as reported earning increased, especially above ~3sd or ~$75,500, the variation in scores decreases. Institutes reporting high graduate earnings also saw their index score remain pretty consistent at
+/- 1sd of their average score.

The second plot for low earning institutes, while the range of earning is smaller, showed score variation to be more consistent at than seen in the high earning plot ~+/- 2sd.

Searching for any relationship through regression analysis, the regression for index score against high earning schools showed no relationship. Because the search for colleges has season in relation to the start of school in the fall, the regression controlled for monthly variations.

As expected with a significance at the 5% level, there is no relationship between high reported earning and institutes interest. This mostly results from the difficultly in gather earning data before 2015.
